Anonymous Sun 14 Mar 2021 21:10:06 No.37084700 Report
Quoted By: >>37084852 >>37084897
>>37083961
Humans sweat all over our bodies with eccrine sweat glands. Other animals have eccrine sweat glands near exclusively in their paws to help increase friction. Apocrine sweat glands are present in out armpits and crotches, yet only aid to an extent the cooling provided by the eccrine sweat glands. In other animals apocrine sweat glands are present across the whole rest of the body. However, in other animals they have a completely different purpose—communication. Naturally, as they aren't used for any thermoregulation in animals, they are much less active as well. The sweat that we produce from our armpits and crotches would be like an invisible ink to us but a giant flashing billboard to them. The only exception to any of this is to hoofed animals, some of which also use apocrine sweat glands as their primary method of thermoregulation. Even of those, the only ones who do to any significant degree are equines, yet they still use sweat as a thermoregulator much less than humans.
Tl;dr they'd just smell like animals irl do (admittedly after a bath which anthros would probably do significantly more often than we do for animals irl) and they'd be able to smell our emotions.
